{"hits": {"hits": [{"created": "2024-08-29T10:08:18.613002+00:00", "modified": "2025-10-07T01:23:23.691741+00:00", "id": 13463376, "conceptrecid": "13463375", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.13463376", "conceptdoi": "10.5281/zenodo.13463375", "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.13463376", "metadata": {"title": "The magnitude of roadkill in Taiwan: Patterns and consequences revealed by citizen science", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.13463376", "publication_date": "2019", "description": "(Uploaded by Plazi for the Bat Literature Project) Roadkill is among the most severe and insidious causes of impoverishment of vertebrate populations. As large roadkill databases develop, inferences from roadkill data can inform landscape-scale studies with broad conservation aims. The Taiwan Roadkill Observation Network (TaiRON) is one of the largest roadkill databases, and we elucidated taxonomic, seasonal, and temporal trends of roadkill in Taiwan, as well as patterns of protected species roadkill. Notably, the study revealed that snakes were the largest proportion of all roadkill (35%) and 26% of snake roadkills were of protected species. Additionally, the top 23 species of a total 496 species ranked by roadkill abundance made up 50% of the observations. During winter, there were significantly fewer roadkill observations of bats, lizards, and snakes, but birds and mammals had fairly consistent roadkill across seasons. Additionally, 19% percent of the observations were of protected species. The staggering magnitude and extent of roadkill observations collected by TaiRON indicates a clear impact of roads of on Taiwan's vertebrate fauna. The patterns demonstrate that certain taxonomic groups are disproportionately killed on roads, and a small number of species account for most of the mortality. Additionally, certain seasons account for higher frequency of road kills, especially for ectothermic taxa. These are important insights, as this means that there are groups that are highly and disproportionately affected by roads. We hope this first synthesis of all data from TaiRON provides an understanding of the magnitude of roadkill in Taiwan to inform conservation action.", "access_right": "restricted", "creators": [{"name": "Chyn, Kristina", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Lin, Te-En", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Chen, Yu-Kai", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Chen, Chih-Yun", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Fitzgerald, Lee A.", "affiliation": null}], "keywords": ["Biodiversity", "Mammalia", "Chiroptera", "Chordata", "Animalia", "bats", "bat"], "related_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/2e6302b23196f9ed356699c2a0050903", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://sha256/a1548942b887811d6336ddd1d4158d12f66296c979a2fdd9da7f9f62d5ad5b33", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "zotero://select/groups/5435545/items/7Y5SGJST", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://zotero.org/groups/5435545/items/7Y5SGJST", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://linker.bio/cut:hash://md5/7cfa7c86440c0f486392c473fc6f3f53!/b344161-346616", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://md5/330417efcaa2560c9b8ebcd6fae17ce0", "relation": "isPartOf", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "10.5281/zenodo.1410543", "relation": "isCompiledBy", "resource_type": "software", "scheme": "doi"}], "custom": {"dwc:class": ["Mammalia"], "dwc:kingdom": ["Animalia"], "dwc:order": ["Chiroptera"], "dwc:phylum": ["Chordata"]}, "resource_type": {"title": "Journal article", "type": "publication", "subtype": "article"}, "journal": {"pages": "317-326", "title": "Biological Conservation", "volume": "237"}, "alternate_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/2e6302b23196f9ed356699c2a0050903"}, {"identifier": "urn:lsid:zotero.org:groups:5435545:items:7Y5SGJST"}, {"identifier": "10.1016/j.biocon.2019.07.014"}], "communities": [{"id": "biosyslit"}, {"id": "batlit"}], "relat